landers, Belgium","Europe":"Europe","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Aa","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Jewish (from North Africa): from the male personal name <i>ʿAdda</i>, used in the Maghreb, a pet form of any of the many names beginning with <i>ʿAbd</i> ‘servant’.","Turkish: ornamental or topographic name from <i>ada</i> ‘island’.","Filipino: unexplained."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"van","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Ivan   or   Evan  , as in the case of the American film actor  Van Heflin  (  1910–71 , born  Emmett Evan Heflin ) and the Northern Irish singer  Van Morrison  (  b. 1945  as  George Ivan Morrison )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"der","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Graaf Jean van der Aa I was born about 1313, his father, Gerhard van Der Aa, was 27 and his mother, Anne de Bruges Herit. Gruuthuyse, was 28. He married Margaretha Beatrix van Gistel before 1320, in Europe. He died about 1360, at the age of 49."},"et":{"Abt 1313–Abt 1360":"umbes 1313–umbes 1360","1313–1360":"1313–1360","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1305–1364":"1305–1364","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1325–1400":"1325–1400","1335–1370":"1335–1370","1339–1384":"1339–1384","1287–1327":"1287–1327","1287–1344":"1287–1344","before 1335":"enne 1335","1384":"1384","Abt 1313":"umbes 1313","Abt 1335":"umbes 1335","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1327":"1327","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1335":"1335","1313":"1313","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1344":"1344","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","um 1327":"umbes 1327","1339":"1339","Brugge, West Flanders, Belgium":"Brugge, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Europe":"Europe","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1313–Abt 1360":"noin 1313–noin 1360","1313–1360":"1313–1360","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1305–1364":"1305–1364","1310–Female":"1310–Kuollut","1325–1400":"1325–1400","1335–1370":"1335–1370","1339–1384":"1339–1384","1287–1327":"1287–1327","1287–1344":"1287–1344","be